<img class="size-full wp-image-1541341 aligncenter" src="https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SARS.jpg?resize=640%2C360&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="640" height="360" srcset="https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SARS.jpg?w=640&amp;ssl=1 640w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SARS.jpg?resize=300%2C169&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SARS.jpg?resize=58%2C33&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SARS.jpg?resize=260%2C146&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SARS.jpg?resize=200%2C113&amp;ssl=1 200w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" data-recalc-dims="1" />A petitioner, Timothy Ogbeye, on Monday slumped while narrating his ordeal before the National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) panel. The NHRC independent  panel is investigating violations of rights by defunct Special Anti-Robbery Squad (SARS) and other police units. Ogbeye, was later revived and taken to the hospital. Following this, Garba Tetengi, SAN, who stood in for the panel Chairman, rtd Justice Suleiman Galadima, adjourned further hearing until March 24. NAN reports that in his petition, Ogbeye alleged that he was unlawfully arrested, detained , assaulted, tortured and given inhuman and degrading treatment by the SARS operatives. The petition was against Insp Oriyomi Aregbelo; Uche Onnonogbo; Andrew James and Patrick Agbazue, all of the defunct SARS, Awkuzu, Anambra, as well the Officer in Charge, defunct SARS, Anambra. Others are the Commissioner of Police, Anambra and the Inspector-General of Police. The petitioner, a car dealer alleged that on Jan. 22, 2020 operatives of SARS, visited his car stand, disguised as customers. He said the policemen arrested him, his younger brother and took five cars, including a Toyota Venza from his stand. The petitioner alleged that he taken to  Kwali Area Council, FCT where he met a man who sold a car to in 2019. He alleged that he was taken to Anambra after five days in detention and asked to pay N2 million to be set free. Ogbeye in his petition said he refused to pay the N2million and he was tortured by SARS operatives and paraded as an armed robber. He said he was forced to crawl like a snake and bark like a dog. Ogbeye demanded N10 million from the police as compensation for violation of his rights.(NAN) Vanguard News Nigeria A widow,  Loveth Uloko, on Tuesday prayed the National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) panel to order the police to pay her N500 million as compensation for the death of her husband, Abraham, Uloko, in the hands of SARS. The NHRC independent panel is investigating alleged violations of rights by the disbanded SARS and other police… February 16, 2021 In "News" …As petitioner dies before case is heard …Bayelsa panel receives 35 petitions By Luminous Jannamike & Onozure Dania The Coalition of Civil Society Organisations, yesterday, called on the #EndSARS Judicial Panels of Inquiry in Anambra and Akwa Ibom states to subpoena operatives of the defunct Special Anti-Robbery Squad, SARS, who… November 25, 2020 In "News" A case bordering on alleged abuse of office came up for hearing at the ongoing Independent Investigative Panel on SARS and other units of the Nigeria Police. December 16, 2020 In "News"